## Item 1 — Live provider acceptance proof

- **Who:** Research Desk provider integration owners; repository
  /Users/fortunevieyra/Documents/Github/ai-projects/autonomous-research-system;
  Tavily, arXiv, and OpenAI live-mode surfaces.
- **What:** Run and archive credentialed live acceptance proof without weakening
  the existing demo/live integrity boundary.
- **How discovered:** The final validation inventory confirmed that live tests are
  intentionally marked and deselected in the default suite, and no provider
  credentials were used in this completed build.
- **Where to fix:** tests/live/test_live_providers.py, docs/evaluation.md,
  docs/security.md, src/research_system/tools/tavily.py,
  src/research_system/tools/arxiv.py, and src/research_system/llm.py.
- **When it appears:** When RESEARCH_MODE is live and a user selects Web, arXiv,
  or the OpenAI model adapter.
- **Detailed description:** Unit tests prove provider normalization, retries,
  limits, invalid-URL skipping, prompt budgets, and arXiv pacing with mocked
  transports. They do not prove current provider credentials, quota, dashboard
  policy, real response formats, latency, or external retention behavior.
- **Acceptance criteria:**
  - Run make test-live with intentionally provisioned test credentials.
  - Capture provider name, model, timestamp, query count, latency, and integrity
    labels without capturing secrets or private content.
  - Prove no demo_fixture source appears in a live result.
  - Prove a provider failure is visible as a warning while surviving evidence
    remains correctly labeled.
  - Archive the proof separately from local deterministic and production claims.
- **Definition of done:** A dated live-provider proof document records successful
  Tavily, arXiv, and OpenAI calls or exact provider-specific blockers; results
  read back through the normal run ledger; the default keyless suite remains
  network-isolated; no credentials enter git, logs, screenshots, or handoffs.
- **Reason why the issue exists:** Credentials were not supplied for this task,
  and silently using personal or production credentials would violate scope,
  cost, privacy, and proof-boundary requirements.
- **Priority:** P2.
- **Why this priority:** It is required before claiming live-provider acceptance,
  but it does not block the complete deterministic local product delivered here.
- **How to prevent regressions:** Keep live tests opt-in, retain the no-fixture
  live contract, pin adapter schemas, and require a dated proof on provider or
  model changes.
- **How to ensure proper testing:** Use pytest live tests for provider contracts
  and Playwright for any browser E2E. Do not introduce Cypress E2E.
- **Audit policies:** Secret-safe execution, validation-proof separation,
  source-integrity readback, provider data-flow disclosure, dependency audit,
  and no-environment-dump policy.
- **Other considerations:**
  - Confirm provider data retention and organizational approval before sensitive
    PDF or memory content is submitted.
  - Keep cost, rate-limit, and retry budgets bounded.
  - Do not relabel live results as production proof.

## Item 2 — Hosted multi-user security and persistence

- **Who:** Future hosting/platform owner for Research Desk.
- **What:** Replace the intentionally single-user local boundary with authenticated,
  tenant-isolated hosted infrastructure.
- **How discovered:** Architecture and security review confirmed that the current
  process-wide engine and SQLite stores are explicitly designed for one local
  writer, while no hosted or production claim is made.
- **Where to fix:** src/research_system/api, src/research_system/engine.py,
  src/research_system/persistence, src/research_system/memory, compose.yaml,
  docs/operations.md, and future infrastructure manifests.
- **When it appears:** Before exposing the UI or API beyond a trusted localhost,
  running multiple replicas, or storing data for more than one user or tenant.
- **Detailed description:** The current runtime has no authentication, authorization,
  tenant key, encryption-at-rest policy, retention/deletion workflow, distributed
  lock, networked checkpointer, centralized rate limiter, or hosted backup service.
  SQLite and the process-wide lock correctly protect the local product but are not
  a horizontal-scaling architecture.
- **Acceptance criteria:**
  - Authenticate every UI and API request.
  - Scope runs, checkpoints, sources, uploads, and memory by immutable tenant and
    user identity.
  - Use a supported networked persistence layer with migrations, encryption,
    backup, restore, and retention proof.
  - Add per-tenant quotas, provider budgets, abuse controls, audit logs, and
    deletion/export workflows.
  - Prove anonymous-to-authenticated and cross-tenant isolation regressions.
- **Definition of done:** Two isolated test tenants can run concurrently without
  reading, mutating, recalling, exporting, or deleting one another's data; backup
  and restore are proven; auth failures are typed; provider costs are attributable;
  hosted health and observability are documented.
- **Reason why the issue exists:** The requested goal was a complete portfolio-grade
  local project, not authorization to create or deploy a production SaaS control
  plane.
- **Priority:** P2 before hosting; P4 while the product remains localhost-only.
- **Why this priority:** Exposure without these controls would be high risk, but no
  current local baseline is broken.
- **How to prevent regressions:** Make tenant identity mandatory in persistence
  schemas and cache keys, add isolation fixtures, and block deployment when auth
  or migration checks fail.
- **How to ensure proper testing:** Add API integration tests, state readback tests,
  concurrency/load tests, and Playwright hosted E2E. Cypress remains component-only
  if a React surface is ever added.
- **Audit policies:** Identity-context regression, state-readback persistence,
  route/API contract mapping, validation-proof selector, deploy-automation hazards,
  least privilege, and secret-safe execution.
- **Other considerations:**
  - Reassess third-party provider terms and regional data residency.
  - Add malware scanning and object storage lifecycle controls for uploads.
  - Separate local, hosted-dev, and production proof.

## Item 3 — Crash recovery, stale-run reconciliation, and request idempotency

- **Who:** ResearchEngine and FastAPI lifecycle owner.
- **What:** Add explicit resume/reconciliation semantics and cross-request
  idempotency for resilient service operation.
- **How discovered:** Checkpoint review proved durable same-thread follow-up state,
  but the engine intentionally starts a new run for every request and does not
  reconcile a process killed between pending, running, and terminal persistence.
- **Where to fix:** src/research_system/engine.py,
  src/research_system/api/routes.py, src/research_system/persistence/runs.py,
  src/research_system/persistence/checkpoints.py, and related integration tests.
- **When it appears:** Process crash, host restart during an active graph, client
  retry after a timeout, or duplicate POST /research submission.
- **Detailed description:** Stable run and thread IDs support readback and
  continuation but do not deduplicate externally repeated requests. A killed run
  can remain pending or running, and there is no public resume/cancel endpoint or
  policy for deciding whether provider calls may be replayed.
- **Acceptance criteria:**
  - Define immutable idempotency-key semantics and persistence.
  - Repeated identical requests return the original run without repeating paid
    provider calls.
  - Startup reconciliation classifies stale runs and either resumes from a safe
    checkpoint or marks them interrupted with an auditable reason.
  - Cancellation has a terminal state and does not corrupt checkpoint history.
  - Recovery tests inject failure at every stage boundary.
- **Definition of done:** Restart and duplicate-request test matrices prove
  exactly-once externally visible semantics where promised, at-most-once paid
  provider calls where feasible, durable terminal state, and a documented policy
  for non-replayable work.
- **Reason why the issue exists:** Reliable distributed execution requires product
  decisions about replay and billing that were outside the local single-process
  goal. The current docs deliberately avoid a crash-resume claim.
- **Priority:** P2 for service deployment; P3 for localhost-only use.
- **Why this priority:** It affects resilience and cost under crashes/retries but
  does not invalidate ordinary local runs or same-thread follow-ups.
- **How to prevent regressions:** Persist idempotency and stage transitions
  transactionally, use failure-injection tests, and forbid untracked provider calls.
- **How to ensure proper testing:** Integration tests with forced process-stage
  failures, concurrent duplicate requests, restart readback, and Playwright only
  for user-visible resume/cancel behavior.
- **Audit policies:** State-readback persistence, route/API contract map,
  provider-cost boundary, deploy-automation hazards, and completion proof labels.
- **Other considerations:**
  - Preserve conversation and source budgets on resume.
  - Do not call checkpoint durability fault tolerance until recovery is proven.
  - Decide retention for interrupted checkpoints.

