# 6. Debugging History & Failure Modes

**Freshness: ✅ High — reproduced and repaired in this session.**

- ChromaDB audit failure: no fixed release. Resolution: removed dependency and
  implemented SQLite vector memory.
- Warning reducer leakage: prior-run warnings survived follow-up. Resolution:
  scalar warning state with explicit same-run merges and regression coverage.
- Evidence starvation: full previous source sets could crowd out new research.
  Resolution: only user-upload evidence is carried as upload priority.
- Demo truth failure: generic words such as source, workflow, memory, or agent
  could trigger unrelated fixtures. Resolution: agent-system or research-quality
  conjunction gate plus negative cases.
- Untrusted rendering: provider/model Markdown could create images or raw HTML.
  Resolution: literal escaping and report sanitization, with UI injection tests.
- arXiv concurrency race: two cache misses could bypass first-request pacing.
  Resolution: serialized search/cache/request lock and concurrent regression.
- PDF failure escape: page extraction RuntimeError could fail the run. Resolution:
  normalized SourceValidationError and per-upload warning boundary.
- Browser ambiguity: duplicate Research Desk headings and mobile sidebar overlay.
  Resolution: level-aware selectors and automatic responsive sidebar state.
- First container build was cancelled because its source became stale and the
  dependency layer was slow. Resolution: cache-mounted two-stage uv sync.
- First port-8501 container E2E reached an unrelated Codebase Intelligence app.
  Resolution: preserve the external app, parameterize host ports, prove on 8505.
- Effective debugging pattern: surface exact terminal result, inspect persisted
  state separately from UI, add the smallest failing regression, then rerun the
  full gate and proof layer.

